  "text": "The R-leap method is an example of a simulation algorithm that generates approximate sample paths by firing a user-specified number of reactions during each step. The R-leap method was described by Auger et al. [CITATION_1] . The R-leap method differs from the tau-leap method in that each 'tau-leap' covers a fixed time interval (with the number of reaction events determined by simulation), whereas the time interval covered by each 'R-leap' must be determined by simulating a random number (though the number of reaction events is fixed).",
